Not only lakes, but mountains in the way. Wall maps are flat but the state isn't. None of that water could reach the fires, and despite reports, it wasn't a valve at the top of the state, but rain at the bottom that helped the fire fighters stop the fires.  

Fortunately it was stopped before more damage was done and there were devastating floods from the release.  Reservoirs hold the water now, while fields are fallow, for release during the growing season when the weather is dry. Farmers rely on it, and it's not only Californians who would suffer, but the rest of the country as well if more water had been wasted and crops were lost.

